00:09:10,288 --> 00:09:12,498
-And when's that gonna be?
-I don't know.

244
00:09:12,582 --> 00:09:16,085
I swear. I have no idea when
my parents are coming back.

245
00:09:23,134 --> 00:09:25,052
You believe i… in fairy tales.

246
00:09:25,136 --> 00:09:27,471
I do not believe in fairy tales.
I'm a man of science.

247
00:09:27,555 --> 00:09:29,973
The Bible serves its purpose.

248
00:09:30,057 --> 00:09:33,143
It is basically a moral set of rules.

249
00:09:33,227 --> 00:09:34,353
A… A road map.

250
00:09:34,437 --> 00:09:35,729
Men are not able

251
00:09:35,813 --> 00:09:38,816
to determine right or
wrong without a road map.

252
00:09:41,277 --> 00:09:43,488
[OVERLAPPING CHATTER IN RUSSIAN]

253
00:09:45,364 --> 00:09:47,908
-Let me guess. Freud?
-Better. The Bible. [LAUGHS]

254
00:09:47,992 --> 00:09:50,786
-Oh, dear. We'll meet for lunch?
-See you there.

255
00:09:50,870 --> 00:09:52,079
Au revoir, messieurs.

256
00:09:52,163 --> 00:09:53,539
-Au revoir.
-Au revoir.

257
00:09:53,623 --> 00:09:57,334
Abe, your wife is very, very attractive.

258
00:09:57,418 --> 00:09:59,753
<i>-Elle est très belle.</i>
-You lucky man.

259
00:09:59,837 --> 00:10:01,380
The luckiest.

260
00:10:01,464 --> 00:10:03,173
So, where were we?

261
00:10:03,257 --> 00:10:05,008
Oh, yes, Sergei's an idiot.

262
00:10:05,092 --> 00:10:07,052
[LAUGHTER]

263
00:10:07,136 --> 00:10:09,138
[OVERLAPPING CHATTER IN RUSSIAN]

264
00:11:38,145 --> 00:11:40,195
["COIN DE RUE" BY JULIETTE GRÉCO PLAYING]

265
00:11:52,951 --> 00:11:56,412
We spent two hours
debating moral nihilism

266
00:11:56,496 --> 00:11:59,541
versus mereological or
compositional nihilism.

267
00:11:59,625 --> 00:12:01,793
At least, I think that's
what we were debating.

268
00:12:01,877 --> 00:12:03,294
I can't be sure.

269
00:12:03,378 --> 00:12:05,630
Either way, it's nihilism, so who cares?

270
00:12:05,714 --> 00:12:07,840
Anyhow, whatever it was,

271
00:12:07,924 --> 00:12:09,842
it got Sergei all steamed up.

272
00:12:09,926 --> 00:12:11,678
He started arguing with Thierry.

273
00:12:11,762 --> 00:12:14,180
Or Rolf. I don't know.
It was someone to the left of me.

274
00:12:14,264 --> 00:12:16,766
And the next thing I
know, Thierry is crying,

275
00:12:16,850 --> 00:12:18,851
Rolf is singing Brecht, and I'm decrying

276
00:12:18,935 --> 00:12:21,020
America's national cynicism.

277
00:12:21,104 --> 00:12:23,523
And no one would let the
other person pay the bill.

278
00:12:23,607 --> 00:12:26,442
It was just a terrific, terrific day.

279
00:12:26,526 --> 00:12:28,404
-Proost.
-Proost.

280
00:12:28,488 --> 00:12:30,906
Today my class went to the Rodin Museum.

281
00:12:30,990 --> 00:12:33,033
Rodin, aha.

282
00:12:33,117 --> 00:12:35,202
It's in this glorious
building that was his studio

283
00:12:35,286 --> 00:12:38,122
and sort of artists'
flophouse at the same time.

284
00:12:38,206 --> 00:12:40,124
It's a museum now. I tell you, Abe,

285
00:12:40,208 --> 00:12:41,875
it took my breath away.

286
00:12:41,959 --> 00:12:45,462
The hands on his
sculptures, they're so powerful.

287
00:12:45,546 --> 00:12:47,548
-Massive.
-Hands are great.

288
00:12:47,632 --> 00:12:49,466
-What is this?
-What does it taste like?

289
00:12:49,550 --> 00:12:52,428
-Rodin loves big hands. Go on.
-I can't imagine

290
00:12:52,512 --> 00:12:54,221
how he did it, how he
would look at nothing,

291
00:12:54,305 --> 00:12:57,349
a block of marble, and see what he saw.

292
00:12:57,433 --> 00:12:58,767
I'd love to show it to you.

293
00:12:58,851 --> 00:13:01,604
-Absolutely. Is it fish?
-Does it taste like fish?

294
00:13:01,688 --> 00:13:03,939
I can't wait to see Rodin's hands.

295
00:13:04,023 --> 00:13:07,693
What do you think, Simone?

296
00:13:07,777 --> 00:13:10,738
What did Mommy make?

297
00:13:10,822 --> 00:13:12,824
["COIN DE RUE" CONTINUES PLAYING]

298
00:13:21,833 --> 00:13:25,044
<i>-Bonne nuit, mon amour.
-Bonne nuit, mon amour.</i>

299
00:13:25,128 --> 00:13:28,589
-You're a wonderful man.
-You're a terrible cook.

300
00:13:30,550 --> 00:13:32,750
["ARTIFICIAL FLOWERS"
BY BOBBY DARIN PLAYING]

301
00:13:34,595 --> 00:13:38,015
<i>♪ Alone in the world ♪</i>

302
00:13:38,099 --> 00:13:41,310
<i>♪ Was poor little Anne ♪</i>

303
00:13:41,394 --> 00:13:45,898
<i>♪ As sweet a young child as you'd find ♪</i>

304
00:13:45,982 --> 00:13:48,567
<i>♪ Her parents had gone ♪</i>

305
00:13:48,651 --> 00:13:51,403
<i>♪ To their final reward… ♪</i>

306
00:13:51,487 --> 00:13:53,489
[PRESSING MACHINE CLANKING]

307
00:13:55,366 --> 00:13:57,451
-Try it again, Tony.
-Back on.

308
00:13:57,535 --> 00:13:59,995
-[MACHINE SPUTTERS]
-Okay, turn it off.

309
00:14:00,079 --> 00:14:02,581
-How long has this thing been out?
-Four or five days?

310
00:14:02,665 --> 00:14:04,208
Why haven't you gotten it fixed?

311
00:14:04,292 --> 00:14:05,959
Jankel, the guy who comes
and fixes the machines,

312
00:14:06,043 --> 00:14:07,461
-he only comes on Fridays.
-Why?

313
00:14:07,545 --> 00:14:09,004
I don't know. It's only Fridays.

314
00:14:09,088 --> 00:14:10,631
Before 1:00.
That's when he goes to temple.

315
00:14:10,715 --> 00:14:12,717
Only on Fridays. Okay.

316
00:14:14,469 --> 00:14:16,303
-Try it again, Tony.
-Back on.

317
00:14:16,387 --> 00:14:17,554
[MACHINE WHIRRING]

318
00:14:17,638 --> 00:14:20,974
Well, it's not Gershwin, but it's moving.

319
00:14:21,058 --> 00:14:22,894
You need a new repairman.

320
00:14:22,978 --> 00:14:25,146
Jankel will be here Friday before 1:00.

321
00:14:25,230 --> 00:14:26,981
You need a repairman who
comes when things break.

322
00:14:27,065 --> 00:14:28,650
-You can't run things like this.
-I can't?

323
00:14:28,734 --> 00:14:30,068
I've only been doing it for 30 years.

324
00:14:30,152 --> 00:14:31,319
What the hell do I know?

325
00:14:31,403 --> 00:14:32,987
You're right. Jankel's gone.

326
00:14:33,071 --> 00:14:35,156
You run a factory.
You need machines that work.

327
00:14:35,240 --> 00:14:37,575
Ah, should I have him killed?
Firing may not be enough.

328
00:14:37,659 --> 00:14:40,328
He comes one day a week.
Not even a full day.

329
00:14:40,412 --> 00:14:42,330
-He leaves at 1:00.
-He should skip temple?

330
00:14:42,414 --> 00:14:45,333
You want the man who fixes
our machines to make God angry?

331
00:14:45,417 --> 00:14:47,585
-How does that end well for us?
-You're getting a new repairman.

332
00:14:47,669 --> 00:14:49,421
No, we're not.
And what the fuck did you put

333
00:14:49,505 --> 00:14:51,589
-a coffee machine in for?
-People need a coffee break.

334
00:14:51,673 --> 00:14:53,591
The whole place is
lining up for free coffee.

335
00:14:53,675 --> 00:14:56,177
-Nobody's working.
-Yes, it's a graveyard.

336
00:14:56,261 --> 00:14:57,846
What are you doing here, anyway, huh?

337
00:14:57,930 --> 00:14:59,848
You were supposed to come
by for a day, look around,

338
00:14:59,932 --> 00:15:01,683
say hi to everyone, see how things are.

339
00:15:01,767 --> 00:15:03,101
That was two weeks ago.

340
00:15:03,185 --> 00:15:04,686
There's a lot of people to say hi to.

341
00:15:04,770 --> 00:15:07,439
Plus, I hear there's free coffee now.

342
00:15:07,523 --> 00:15:09,858
Manny, not sure you
should be smoking there.

343
00:15:09,942 --> 00:15:11,651
I'm by a trash can.

344
00:15:11,735 --> 00:15:13,653
Lots of chemicals and
solvents all over the place.

345
00:15:13,737 --> 00:15:15,613
You remember the
Triangle Shirtwaist fire?

346
00:15:15,697 --> 00:15:16,614
Like it was yesterday.

347
00:15:16,698 --> 00:15:19,033
Get back to work, Manny.

348
00:15:19,117 --> 00:15:21,536
That's the fourth cigarette
break he's taken this morning.

349
00:15:21,620 --> 00:15:23,955
So what?
You're so hot for people taking breaks.

350
00:15:24,039 --> 00:15:25,957
People who work.
I've never seen him work.

351
00:15:26,041 --> 00:15:28,126
-What does Manny do?
-What does he do? Manny does.

352
00:15:28,210 --> 00:15:30,128
That's what Manny does. Manny does.

353
00:15:30,212 --> 00:15:31,796
Frieda, honey, you've been sitting there

354
00:15:31,880 --> 00:15:33,047
for four straight hours.

355
00:15:33,131 --> 00:15:34,299
Get up. Take a break.

356
00:15:34,383 --> 00:15:35,884
You're not chained to the table.

357
00:15:35,968 --> 00:15:37,886
-Are you?
-She's not chained to the table.

358
00:15:37,970 --> 00:15:39,805
Go have some coffee.

359
00:15:40,889 --> 00:15:42,432
Oh, look at her go.

360
00:15:42,516 --> 00:15:44,184
-Jesse Owens.
-Pop.

361
00:15:44,268 --> 00:15:46,936
What? It'll take her an
hour to walk across the room

362
00:15:47,020 --> 00:15:48,438
and an hour to get back.

363
00:15:48,522 --> 00:15:50,023
That's half of her remaining life span.

364
00:15:50,107 --> 00:15:52,358
-Moishe, she won't let me in.
-What?

365
00:15:52,442 --> 00:15:54,360
-Come. Come, come, come, come.
-Where we going?

366
00:15:54,444 --> 00:15:55,987
-Look, look, I'm locked out.
-What's happening?

367
00:15:56,071 --> 00:15:57,489
-Where's he going? Hey.
-Go, go. Get him, get him.

368
00:15:57,573 --> 00:15:58,740
-Hey, hey. Get back here.
-Come back here.

369
00:15:58,824 --> 00:16:01,493
-Do not close the…
-[LOCK CLICKS]

370
00:16:01,577 --> 00:16:03,578
Let me guess, it's worse than I thought.

371
00:16:03,662 --> 00:16:05,413
-Oh, much, much worse.
-Terrific.

372
00:16:05,497 --> 00:16:07,999
None of these numbers add up.
A… And this writing.

373
00:16:08,083 --> 00:16:09,584
At first, I thought it was in Hebrew,

374
00:16:09,668 --> 00:16:11,920
but then I realized parts are in Yiddish.

375
00:16:12,004 --> 00:16:13,671
-[KNOCKING]
-And this is ancient Aramaic,

376
00:16:13,755 --> 00:16:15,757
which has been a dead
language for 2,000 years.

377
00:16:15,841 --> 00:16:18,093
[STAMMERS] Can you
figure out any of the money?

378
00:16:18,177 --> 00:16:20,930
-The figures?
-I think it's a numerical system

379
00:16:21,014 --> 00:16:22,932
-that has eliminated the number six.
-[KEYS JINGLE]

380
00:16:23,016 --> 00:16:24,558
-What?
-[LOCK CLICKS]

381
00:16:24,642 --> 00:16:26,852
Coming in, schmuck.
You lock me out of my own office?

382
00:16:26,936 --> 00:16:28,771
What is she doing with my book?

383
00:16:28,855 --> 00:16:30,731
You think I don't have
a key to my own office?

384
00:16:30,815 --> 00:16:32,900
-These books don't make sense.
-SHIRLEY: Of course they do.

385
00:16:32,984 --> 00:16:35,319
-What do you want to know?
-Well, everything would be nice.

386
00:16:35,403 --> 00:16:37,071
This column is the money we have.

387
00:16:37,155 --> 00:16:38,989
This column is the money we will have

388
00:16:39,073 --> 00:16:40,908
as soon as these people from this column

389
00:16:40,992 --> 00:16:42,243
or that column pay us.

390
00:16:42,327 --> 00:16:43,828
Unless it has a bagel stamp,

391
00:16:43,912 --> 00:16:45,162
which means it's still being negotiated

392
00:16:45,246 --> 00:16:47,748
but we started the work
anyway in case it works out.

393
00:16:47,832 --> 00:16:49,166
Three flags, that
means the check cleared.

394
00:16:49,250 --> 00:16:50,751
Two flowers, that means a half and half.

395
00:16:50,835 --> 00:16:52,920
-A half and half?
-Half check, half cash.

396
00:16:53,004 --> 00:16:54,547
Or half cash, half services.

397
00:16:54,631 --> 00:16:57,132
Or half…
something and half something else.

398
00:16:57,216 --> 00:16:59,593
-You have Kaufman and Hart write this bit?
-Uh, can I

399
00:16:59,677 --> 00:17:03,013
just ask you…
um, there is a Sunny spelled with a "U"

400
00:17:03,097 --> 00:17:05,766
and a Sonny with an "O"
and another with an I-E.

401
00:17:05,850 --> 00:17:07,434
Is that the same Sonny?

402
00:17:07,518 --> 00:17:09,436
Of course it's the same Sonny.

403
00:17:09,520 --> 00:17:11,939
It's Sonny. Sonny from Queens.

404
00:17:12,023 --> 00:17:14,692
-Pop, you need an accountant.
-What are you talking about, accountant?

405
00:17:14,776 --> 00:17:17,111
This is a foolproof system
that I invented myself.

406
00:17:17,195 --> 00:17:18,445
Completely secure.

407
00:17:18,529 --> 00:17:20,281
Only I can understand it.

408
00:17:20,365 --> 00:17:21,490
I don't know.

409
00:17:21,574 --> 00:17:23,450
I'll have you know that
we got audited once.

410
00:17:23,534 --> 00:17:25,119
And when the guy took
one look at this book,

411
00:17:25,203 --> 00:17:26,829
we never saw him again.

412
00:17:26,913 --> 00:17:28,998
I paid him off.
That's why we never saw him again.

413
00:17:29,082 --> 00:17:30,416
-Pop, this is crazy.
-Okay.

414
00:17:30,500 --> 00:17:32,751
Enough. You came, you saw.

415
00:17:32,835 --> 00:17:35,087
Thank you for letting me know
that everything I do is wrong

416
00:17:35,171 --> 00:17:37,047
and your mother's accounting
system is a piece of shit.

417
00:17:37,131 --> 00:17:38,299
It really is a piece of shit.

418
00:17:38,383 --> 00:17:40,134
I'm serious. You and you, out.

419
00:17:40,218 --> 00:17:42,386
Well, all right. But before we leave,

420
00:17:42,470 --> 00:17:44,638
I found this book

421
00:17:44,722 --> 00:17:46,640
in a secret hiding place in the wall.

422
00:17:46,724 --> 00:17:48,893
No! Put that back.
You should not be looking through that.

423
00:17:48,977 --> 00:17:50,895
This is the special loans book.

424
00:17:50,979 --> 00:17:51,896
-Special loans book?
-What?

425
00:17:51,980 --> 00:17:52,897
SHIRLEY: That's personal.

426
00:17:52,981 --> 00:17:54,773
Don't tell me you're borrowing
money from those guys.

427
00:17:54,857 --> 00:17:56,734
-Once in a while.
-I can't believe this.

428
00:17:56,818 --> 00:17:58,736
You see yourself…
the machines break down.

429
00:17:58,820 --> 00:18:00,654
Those machines are expensive.

430
00:18:00,738 --> 00:18:02,907
How else are we supposed
to get that kind of cash?

431
00:18:02,991 --> 00:18:04,992
-From a bank?
-What are you, a big shot?

432
00:18:05,076 --> 00:18:07,411
Banks don't break your
legs or throw you in a river.

433
00:18:07,495 --> 00:18:09,663
I'm seeing amounts here.
I'm seeing names.

434
00:18:09,747 --> 00:18:12,208
But I'm not seeing any dates
for when the loans are due.

435
00:18:12,292 --> 00:18:14,085
Oh, well, we know when the loans are due.

436
00:18:14,169 --> 00:18:16,171
A couple of guys break in
in the middle of the night.

437
00:18:16,255 --> 00:18:18,173
They bust up some chairs and windows.

438
00:18:18,257 --> 00:18:20,091
And that's when we know the loan is due.

439
00:18:20,175 --> 00:18:22,135
-Shirley, stop helping me.
-What?

440
00:18:22,219 --> 00:18:24,137
-What did I do wrong?
-Nothing, Ma. Relax.

441
00:18:24,221 --> 00:18:28,099
Why don't you go get
yourself a cup of coffee.

442
00:18:28,183 --> 00:18:29,267
There's a machine out there now.

443
00:18:29,351 --> 00:18:30,352
There's a coffee machine?

444
00:18:30,436 --> 00:18:32,688
Oh, what a wonderful idea!

445
00:18:34,148 --> 00:18:35,649
Go home.

446
00:18:35,733 --> 00:18:37,609
You know what, Pop, I'm not going home.

447
00:18:37,693 --> 00:18:39,027
I'm staying.

448
00:18:39,111 --> 00:18:40,487
I'm gonna go through
those cockamamie books,

449
00:18:40,571 --> 00:18:42,364
and I'm gonna get things
in shape around here.

450
00:18:42,448 --> 00:18:45,909
I'm gonna start by firing the
low-hanging fruit like Manny.

451
00:18:45,993 --> 00:18:47,754
Manny's not a fruit.
He came to your bar mitzvah.

452
00:18:47,838 --> 00:18:48,244
He's gone.

453
00:18:48,328 --> 00:18:50,080
I'm firing him today. Along with Pete,

454
00:18:50,164 --> 00:18:51,581
who's in the storage room playing cards

455
00:18:51,665 --> 00:18:52,916
with two other guys that I don't know.

456
00:18:53,000 --> 00:18:54,000
They're fired, too.

457
00:18:54,084 --> 00:18:56,252
Every single freeloader
around here, gone.

458
00:18:56,336 --> 00:18:57,921
I'm getting them off the payroll.

459
00:18:58,005 --> 00:19:00,090
I'm gonna find a fucking
seven-day-a-week repairman.

460
00:19:00,174 --> 00:19:02,676
And once I know this place isn't
being run like a mental asylum,

461
00:19:02,760 --> 00:19:05,012
then I'll go home.

462
00:19:07,264 --> 00:19:10,851
SHIRLEY: Oh, this coffee is delicious!

463
00:19:23,363 --> 00:19:25,657
She's got to work on these notes.

464
00:19:25,741 --> 00:19:27,742
Here comes one, with
Andy Griffith bringing it in.

465
00:19:27,826 --> 00:19:29,244
-Andy Griffith!
-[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

466
00:19:29,328 --> 00:19:33,248
Howdy, Steve. Well…

467
00:19:33,332 --> 00:19:35,000
STEVE: Who's next for you?

468
00:19:35,084 --> 00:19:38,044
ANDY: I've got one
here, Steve, from last July,

469
00:19:38,128 --> 00:19:41,464
where they sent up two
mice in a space rocket,

470
00:19:41,548 --> 00:19:43,133
and they… they lost them both.

471
00:19:43,217 --> 00:19:44,384
I heard about that. It's too bad.

472
00:19:44,468 --> 00:19:45,760
How do they plan to find them again?

473
00:19:45,844 --> 00:19:47,512
Well, they got it figured out, Steve.

474
00:19:47,596 --> 00:19:48,972
They figure they're gonna launch a cat.

475
00:19:49,056 --> 00:19:50,432
-A cat. Uh-huh.
-[LAUGHS]: Yeah.

476
00:19:50,516 --> 00:19:52,726
Thank you, Andy.
He'll be back in a little bit.

477
00:19:52,810 --> 00:19:55,145
And now, here come the McGuire Sisters.

478
00:19:55,229 --> 00:19:56,647
[CHEERS AND APPLAUSE]

479
00:20:00,901 --> 00:20:03,236
Night, Susie.

480
00:20:03,320 --> 00:20:06,197
Night, Ethan.

481
00:20:06,281 --> 00:20:08,868
Look. Should we get it for Sergei?

482
